The concierge of a Milan hotel had bragged to a customer that

00:20:06.806 --> 00:20:10.986
he’d been paid to help organise a hitman to kill Maurizio Gucci.

00:20:12.126 --> 00:20:13.566
And who had paid him?

00:20:14.686 --> 00:20:16.796
If you didn’t know, perhaps you’d guessed it.

00:20:17.146 --> 00:20:19.906
It was Patrizia, Maurizio Gucci’s ex-wife.

00:20:20.676 --> 00:20:24.896
And the more the police investigated Patrizia, the more guilty she seemed.

00:20:25.386 --> 00:20:29.796
She had not exactly kept it a secret that she despised her ex-husband.

00:20:30.596 --> 00:20:33.926
After their divorce, she had left him threatening messages,

00:20:34.196 --> 00:20:37.876
in one even saying, “For you, it is hell to come.”

00:20:38.696 --> 00:20:43.696
And even less subtly, she had asked just about everyone she knew whether they could

00:20:43.696 --> 00:20:48.726
help her dispose of her ex-husband, even talking about it with her divorce lawyer.

00:20:49.836 --> 00:20:52.926
Her behaviour after his death was suspicious, too.

00:20:53.646 --> 00:20:58.766
On the day he died, she had written just one word in her diary: paradise.

00:20:59.856 --> 00:21:05.376
And, just three hours after he died, she had drawn up a notice to evict

00:21:05.436 --> 00:21:10.246
Paola, to kick Paola out from the apartment she had shared with Maurizio.

00:21:10.886 --> 00:21:16.786
She seemed too prepared for her ex-husband's death, almost as if she had known it would happen.

00:21:18.056 --> 00:21:24.233
The final, damning piece of evidence came after the police wire-tapped the hotel concierge’s car.

00:21:25.146 --> 00:21:28.536
They caught members of the group who had helped plan and carry

00:21:28.536 --> 00:21:31.686
out the murder talking about their payment from Patrizia.

00:21:32.426 --> 00:21:35.246
They were unhappy with the amount she had paid them and

00:21:35.426 --> 00:21:39.176
were beginning to hatch a plan to extort more out of her.

00:21:40.296 --> 00:21:43.986
But before anything could come of it, the police turned up at

00:21:43.996 --> 00:21:48.646
Patrizia’s doorstep on the morning of the 31st of January 1997.

00:21:49.156 --> 00:21:50.726
They were there to arrest her.

00:21:51.986 --> 00:21:56.580
Seemingly calm and unsurprised by this, Patrizia had just

00:21:56.580 --> 00:21:59.590
one thing she wanted to do before she was taken to prison.

00:22:00.280 --> 00:22:03.790
She had to go and put on a fur coat and fine jewellery.

00:22:04.960 --> 00:22:07.840
At her trial, she maintained her innocence.

00:22:08.250 --> 00:22:12.700
But, with 43 boxes of evidence presented against her, she was quickly

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:17.870
found guilty and sentenced to 29 years for arranging an assassination.

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:24.190
In 2011, she actually got an early chance at freedom through what's called a

00:22:24.190 --> 00:22:28.530
work-release programme, meaning you can get out of prison if you get a job.

00:22:29.370 --> 00:22:33.640
However, she turned this opportunity down, saying that she had never

00:22:33.640 --> 00:22:37.670
worked a day in her life and she sure as hell wasn’t going to start now.

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:43.060
Five years later she was finally released after serving 18 years.

00:22:43.860 --> 00:22:49.390
Despite her previous comments about never having had a job, she has even expressed an interest

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:56.140
in working for Gucci again because, according to her, she is “the most Gucci of them all.”

